  "prompt": "A shop was selling 3 chocolates for Re. 1 and if you return three wrappers you get 1 free. If so, how many chocolates can you get for Rs. 45?",
  "response": "To determine how many chocolates you can get for Rs. 45, given that the shop sells 3 chocolates for Re. 1 and allows you to exchange 3 wrappers for 1 free chocolate, we can break the problem into two parts: the initial purchase and the free chocolates obtained from wrappers.\n\n1. **Calculate initial chocolates purchased with Rs. 45**:\n   - Since the shop sells 3 chocolates for Re. 1, for Rs. 45 you can buy:\n     \\[\n     45 \\text{ Rs} \\times 3 \\text{ chocolates/Rs.} = 135 \\text{ chocolates}\n     \\]\n\n2. **Calculate how many free chocolates you can get from wrappers**:\n   - Each chocolate comes with a wrapper, so after consuming the 135 chocolates, you will have 135 wrappers.\n   - You can exchange 3 wrappers for 1 free chocolate, so the number of free chocolates you can get from 135 wrappers is:\n     \\[\n     \\left\\lfloor \\frac{135 \\text{ wrappers}}{3 \\text{ wrappers/chocolate}} \\right\\rfloor = 45 \\text{ free chocolates}\n     \\]\n\n3. **Count the total chocolates**:\n   - Total chocolates = chocolates purchased + free chocolates\n     \\[\n     \\text{Total chocolates} = 135 + 45 = 180\n     \\]\n\nThus, for Rs. 45, you can get a total of **180 chocolates**.",
